    "Specifically, convex polyhedra (or equivalently, systems of linear inequalities) are used to represent and analyze the relationships between variables in a program.",
    "In this context, each dimension of a polyhedron typically represents the value of a data location (such as a register or memory address), and the invariants consist of conjunctions of inequalities on these data locations.",
    "This representation allows for more precise analysis of program behavior and execution time bounds [43].",
    "The resulting symbolic WCET formula is then simplified and embedded for real-time evaluation.",
